Key Foundational Works and Researchers
César Ojeda-Linares and colleagues (2024) published the seminal review "The dawn of ethnomicrobiology: an interdisciplinary research field on interactions between humans and microorganisms" in the Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine. It defines the field as examining management practices, knowledge systems, and biocultural diversity in human-microbe relationships (beyond just fermentation to include agriculture, health, preservation, and more). It emphasizes sensory perception (smell, taste, texture) of microbes and calls for theoretical advancement from descriptive to integrative approaches. 

