Future Directions
The field is poised for growth toward "evolutionary ethnomicrobiology," applied outcomes (e.g., microbiome-informed conservation, novel ferments), and policy relevance (food systems, health, biodiversity). Emphasis on community-led research, multi-omics integration, and addressing the "hidden" microbial worlds in ethnobiology. 

pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

Overall, ethnomicrobiology represents a maturing niche within ethnobiology, with high potential for addressing 21st-century challenges like sustainable food production and human-microbiome health, while honoring long-standing cultural expertise in managing the invisible biosphere. Research output is increasing but remains concentrated among a core group of scholars; broader adoption could rapidly expand the landscape."

