"Ethnomicrobiology, as a nascent formal field (primarily framed in Ojeda-Linares et al. 2024), does not yet possess fully crystallized, standalone paradigms. It operates as a distinct interdisciplinary (and transdisciplinary) subfield within ethnobiology, adapting and extending established ethnobiological paradigms while incorporating insights from microbiology, ecology, anthropology, multispecies ethnography, and sensory studies.

pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

Core Positioning and Distinctive Features
The foundational paper positions ethnomicrobiology as examining management practices, knowledge systems, and biocultural relationships with microorganisms. It emphasizes:
Sensory and empirical epistemology: Reliance on observable effects (taste, smell, texture, preservation, fermentation outcomes, health impacts) rather than primarily visual identification.
"Microbial managers" and traditional ecological knowledge (TEK) of invisible consortia.
Co-evolutionary and multispecies entanglements: Humans as active selectors/domesticators of microbial communities (e.g., in fermentation starters or soil practices).
Biocultural conservation: Microbes as part of "hidden" landscapes threatened by industrialization and cultural loss. 

link.springer.com

The field explicitly aims to evolve from descriptive cataloging (e.g., documenting ferments) to theoretical, integrative, and applied approaches, including evolutionary dynamics, ontologies, and politics of knowledge. 

