Methodological Paradigms
Research typically blends:
Ethnographic/qualitative (interviews, participant observation, sensory analysis).
Microbiological/quantitative (metagenomics, culture methods, metabolomics).
Integrative/transdisciplinary (community-led, experimental archaeology, AI/predictive modeling of communities). 

researchgate.net

In summary, ethnomicrobiology’s paradigms are hybrid, integrative, and still forming at the "dawn" of the field. They are rooted in ethnobiology’s pluralistic traditions but distinguished by a focus on the invisible microbial world, sensory knowledge, co-evolution, and ethical/political reconfigurations of multispecies relationships. The ongoing special collection and related lectures (e.g., Ojeda-Linares in 2026) are key venues where these paradigms are being refined. Future work is likely to strengthen evolutionary, onto-epistemic, and applied sustainability frameworks."

